---
import { publicSection } from "../../data/sections";
import PullQuote from "../PullQuote.astro";
import SourceList from "../SourceList.astro";
---

<section id="public" aria-labelledby="public-heading">
	<div class="section-label reveal-left">Public Services</div>
	<h2 id="public-heading" class="reveal" style="transition-delay: 0.1s">
		What Markets<br />Fail to Deliver
	</h2>
	<p class="section-intro reveal" style="transition-delay: 0.2s">
		When healthcare is a commodity and housing is an investment vehicle,
		human welfare becomes subordinate to profit margins. The countries
		that fare best are not those that embraced the market — they are those
		that rejected it. Socialist development demonstrates what is possible
		even under hostile conditions. The record is unequivocal.
	</p>
	<div class="country-grid">
		<div class="country-card reveal">
			<div class="country-name">South Africa</div>
			<div class="system-tag capitalist">Extractive Capitalism</div>
			<dl>
				<div class="metric-row"><dt class="metric-label">Life Expectancy</dt><dd class="metric-val bad">66 yrs <span class="sr-only">(poor)</span></dd></div>
				<div class="metric-row"><dt class="metric-label">Income Gini</dt><dd class="metric-val bad" title="2014 survey data — most recent World Bank figure">0.63 (2014 survey) <span class="sr-only">(poor)</span></dd></div>
				<div class="metric-row"><dt class="metric-label">Unemployment</dt><dd class="metric-val bad">31.9% <span class="sr-only">(poor)</span></dd></div>
				<div class="metric-row"><dt class="metric-label">Child Poverty</dt><dd class="metric-val bad">~62% <span class="sr-only">(poor)</span></dd></div>
				<div class="metric-row"><dt class="metric-label">HDI Rank</dt><dd class="metric-val bad">#114 <span class="sr-only">(poor)</span></dd></div>
			</dl>
		</div>
		<div class="country-card reveal" style="transition-delay: 0.08s">
			<div class="country-name">USA</div>
			<div class="system-tag capitalist">Market Capitalism</div>
			<dl>
				<div class="metric-row"><dt class="metric-label">Life Expectancy</dt><dd class="metric-val bad">79.0 yrs <span class="sr-only">(poor)</span></dd></div>
				<div class="metric-row"><dt class="metric-label">Income Gini</dt><dd class="metric-val bad">0.49 <span class="sr-only">(poor)</span></dd></div>
				<div class="metric-row"><dt class="metric-label">Healthcare OOP</dt><dd class="metric-val bad" title="OOP as % of total health expenditure (WHO). US absolute OOP costs per capita remain highest in the OECD.">11% <span class="sr-only">(poor)</span></dd></div>
				<div class="metric-row"><dt class="metric-label">Child Poverty</dt><dd class="metric-val bad">14% <span class="sr-only">(poor)</span></dd></div>
				<div class="metric-row"><dt class="metric-label">HDI Rank</dt><dd class="metric-val bad">#20 <span class="sr-only">(poor)</span></dd></div>
			</dl>
		</div>
		<div class="country-card reveal" style="transition-delay: 0.16s">
			<div class="country-name">UK</div>
			<div class="system-tag capitalist">Austerity Capitalism</div>
			<dl>
				<div class="metric-row"><dt class="metric-label">Life Expectancy</dt><dd class="metric-val">81.4 yrs</dd></div>
				<div class="metric-row"><dt class="metric-label">Income Gini</dt><dd class="metric-val">0.33</dd></div>
				<div class="metric-row"><dt class="metric-label">Healthcare OOP</dt><dd class="metric-val">15%</dd></div>
				<div class="metric-row"><dt class="metric-label">Child Poverty</dt><dd class="metric-val bad">22% <span class="sr-only">(poor)</span></dd></div>
				<div class="metric-row"><dt class="metric-label">HDI Rank</dt><dd class="metric-val">#15</dd></div>
			</dl>
		</div>
		<div class="country-card reveal" style="transition-delay: 0.1s">
			<div class="country-name">Norway</div>
			<div class="system-tag socialist">Social Democracy</div>
			<dl>
				<div class="metric-row"><dt class="metric-label">Life Expectancy</dt><dd class="metric-val good">83.2 yrs <span class="sr-only">(strong)</span></dd></div>
				<div class="metric-row"><dt class="metric-label">Income Gini</dt><dd class="metric-val good">0.26 <span class="sr-only">(strong)</span></dd></div>
				<div class="metric-row"><dt class="metric-label">Healthcare OOP</dt><dd class="metric-val">14%</dd></div>
				<div class="metric-row"><dt class="metric-label">Child Poverty</dt><dd class="metric-val good">10.6% <span class="sr-only">(strong)</span></dd></div>
				<div class="metric-row"><dt class="metric-label">HDI Rank</dt><dd class="metric-val good">#2 <span class="sr-only">(strong)</span></dd></div>
			</dl>
		</div>
		<div class="country-card reveal" style="transition-delay: 0.18s">
			<div class="country-name">Cuba</div>
			<div class="system-tag socialist" title="All metrics achieved under 60+ years of US economic blockade">Socialism Under Blockade</div>
			<dl>
				<div class="metric-row"><dt class="metric-label">Life Expectancy</dt><dd class="metric-val good">78.3 yrs <span class="sr-only">(strong)</span></dd></div>
				<div class="metric-row"><dt class="metric-label">Income Gini</dt><dd class="metric-val good" title="~0.38 (estimated; no independent verification available — likely higher post-2020)">∼0.38 <span class="sr-only">(strong)</span></dd></div>
				<div class="metric-row"><dt class="metric-label">Healthcare OOP</dt><dd class="metric-val good">~4% <span class="sr-only">(strong)</span></dd></div>
				<div class="metric-row"><dt class="metric-label">Child Poverty</dt><dd class="metric-val good" title="Based on Cuban government statistics — independent verification unavailable">&lt;5% <span class="sr-only">(strong)</span></dd></div>
				<div class="metric-row"><dt class="metric-label">Doctors / 1000</dt><dd class="metric-val good" title="World Bank 2021. A significant proportion are deployed abroad on medical missions.">9.4 <span class="sr-only">(strong)</span></dd></div>
			</dl>
		</div>
		<div class="country-card reveal" style="transition-delay: 0.26s">
			<div class="country-name">China</div>
			<div class="system-tag socialist" title="Lifted 800 million from poverty under socialist state direction, adapting planning to global pressures">Socialism With Adaptation</div>
			<dl>
				<div class="metric-row"><dt class="metric-label">Life Expectancy</dt><dd class="metric-val good">79.0 yrs <span class="sr-only">(strong)</span></dd></div>
				<div class="metric-row"><dt class="metric-label">Literacy Rate</dt><dd class="metric-val good">97% <span class="sr-only">(strong)</span></dd></div>
				<div class="metric-row"><dt class="metric-label">Extreme Poverty</dt><dd class="metric-val good" title="Under China's national poverty line. World Bank international line ($2.15/day) gives ~5%.">&lt;1%† <span class="sr-only">(strong)</span></dd></div>
				<div class="metric-row"><dt class="metric-label">HDI Rank</dt><dd class="metric-val good">#77 <span class="sr-only">(strong)</span></dd></div>
				<div class="metric-row"><dt class="metric-label">Lifted from Poverty</dt><dd class="metric-val good">800M+ <span class="sr-only">(strong)</span></dd></div>
			</dl>
		</div>
	</div>
	<aside class="global-south-callout reveal" aria-label="On Social Democracy">
		<h3>On Social Democracy</h3>
		<p>
			Social democratic states achieve genuinely better outcomes for their
			citizens than raw market capitalism does — better healthcare, lower
			poverty, stronger labour rights. These gains are real and hard-won.
			But the prosperity that makes them possible rests on a foundation
			that cannot be universalised.
		</p>
		<p>
			Western European wealth was built substantially on colonial
			extraction and is sustained through trade relationships that
			systematically disadvantage the Global South. The same multilateral
			institutions — the IMF and World Bank — that protect European
			capital impose structural adjustment on developing nations,
			stripping them of the very policy tools used to build Western
			welfare states. A country cannot pursue the Nordic model if the IMF
			controls its fiscal policy.
		</p>
		<p>
			Social democracy is a checkpoint, not a destination — a more humane
			form of capitalism that has always rested on an exploited periphery.
			This is the neocolonial order it depends on.
		</p>
		<p>
			Cuba and China demonstrate that socialist governance — even under
			decades of economic warfare from capitalist nations — can deliver
			universal healthcare, eliminate mass illiteracy, and drive
			development. Cuba, under a six-decade US blockade, developed and
			exported its own COVID-19 vaccines and deploys medical brigades
			active in 50+ countries at peak — among the largest international
			medical deployments globally. China eliminated extreme poverty for
			800 million people within living memory, built the world's largest
			public healthcare expansion, and achieved near-universal literacy in
			a generation. Their adaptations are not failures of socialism but
			evidence of its resilience under siege.
		</p>
		<PullQuote data={publicSection.pullQuote} reveal={false} />
	</aside>
	<SourceList items={publicSection.sources} />
</section>
